1. Code Modification Policy

Always analyze existing code before generating new code.

Prefer modifying and improving existing implementations over creating new ones.

If a feature is replaced, remove all obsolete related code.

Never leave:

Unused variables

Unused imports

Dead code

Commented-out legacy code

Duplicate logic

Ensure the final codebase contains no redundant or unused elements.

2. Simplicity & Engineering Discipline

Prioritize clarity over cleverness.

Avoid over-engineering.

Do not introduce advanced patterns or abstractions unless clearly necessary.

Write code at the level of a strong intermediate developer:

Practical

Clean

Maintainable

Keep implementations straightforward and readable.

3. Clean Architecture & Structure

Project uses Clean Architecture with Provider for state management.
Keep it simple — start with the scanning-sections pattern and extend as needed.

Folder structure (features):
lib/
  main.dart              — App entry point only
  app.dart               — MaterialApp, theme, routes
  features/
    <feature_name>/
      presentation/
        providers/       — ChangeNotifier classes (extends ChangeNotifier)
        screens/         — Full-screen widgets
        widgets/         — Reusable UI within the feature

Rules for new features:
- One feature = one folder under lib/features/
- State: use Provider (ChangeNotifier + ChangeNotifierProvider)
- Screens: StatelessWidget + context.read<T>() or Consumer<T> for UI
- Follow the scanning sections feature as reference: features/scanning_sections/

Follow a logical and scalable folder structure.

Maintain separation of concerns.

Extract reusable logic into shared utilities/services when appropriate.

Before creating a new function, verify whether similar functionality already exists and reuse it.

Use consistent, meaningful, and concise naming conventions.

4. Production-Ready Standards

All generated code must be production-ready.

Include proper error handling.

Consider realistic edge cases.

Avoid unnecessary API calls.

Optimize performance where reasonable.

Do not expose sensitive data.

Ensure stability and maintainability.

5. Comments Policy

Do not over-comment.

Only add comments when:

Explaining non-obvious logic

Documenting business rules

Clarifying important architectural decisions

Avoid commenting obvious behavior.

6. Performance & API Discipline

Avoid duplicate API requests.

Prevent unnecessary computations.

Reuse existing API utilities when available.

Handle async logic properly and safely.

Avoid inefficient patterns.

7. Refactoring Rules

When modifying code:

Improve clarity where possible.

Remove duplication.

Simplify complex logic.

Do not change functionality unless explicitly requested.

Ensure refactored code remains stable and coherent.

8. Behavioral Constraints

Generate only what is required — no unnecessary expansion.

Do not assume missing requirements.

If instructions are unclear, request clarification.

Do not create new files unless necessary.

Clearly indicate structural changes when introduced.